{"title_page": "Giancarlo Esposito", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| image              = Giancarlo Esposito SXSW 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Esposito at the 2017 [[South by Southwest]] Festival\n| birth_name         = Giancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1958|4|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| nationality        = American, Italian\n| occupation         = Actor and director\n| yearsactive        = 1966\u2013present\n| spouse             = Joy McManigal<br />({{abbr|m.|married}} 1995; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 2015)\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Giancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292a\u014b\u02c8karlo d\u0292u\u02c8z\u025bppe ales\u02c8sandro e\u02c8sp\u0254\u02d0zito}}; born 26 April 1958) is an Italian-American actor and director. He has played [[Gus Fring]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] shows ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' and also plays the character on ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', a role for which he won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series Award]] at the [[Critics' Choice Television Award|2012 Critics' Choice Television Awards]] and was nominated for an [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards#Supporting performances|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] at the [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012 Primetime Emmy Awards]] and again at the [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019 Primetime Emmy Awards]]. He appeared as [[Moff Gideon]] in the live-action ''[[Star Wars]]'' series ''[[The Mandalorian]]'' on [[Disney+]] which premiered in 2019.\n\nHe has appeared in [[Spike Lee]] films such as ''[[Do the Right Thing]]'', ''[[School Daze]]'', and ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]''. His feature film appearances include ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]]'', ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]'', ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'', and ''[[King of New York]]''. He has played Tom Neville in the [[NBC]] series ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'' and Sidney Glass / [[Magic Mirror (Snow White)|Magic Mirror]] on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. He has had roles in two [[Netflix]] original series: ''[[The Get Down]]'', wherein he portrays Pastor Ramon Cruz, and ''[[Dear White People (TV series)|Dear White People]]'', which he narrates. He also voiced and portrayed \"The Dentist\" in the video game ''[[Payday 2]]''.\n\n== Early life ==\nGiancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito was born in [[Copenhagen]], the son of Giovanni Esposito aka John C. Esposito (1931\u20132002), an [[Italians|Italian]] stagehand and carpenter from [[Naples]], and Elizabeth Foster aka Leesa Foster (1926\u20132017), an [[African-American]] opera and nightclub singer from [[Alabama]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te8TCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Giovanni+Esposito+elizabeth+foster|title=Feeling Italian: The Art of Ethnicity in America|last=Ferraro|first=Thomas J.|date=2005|isbn=978-0-8147-2730-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Esposito,_Giancarlo/Biography/|title=Giancarlo Esposito Pictures, Biography, Filmography, News, Videos|accessdate=2009-04-10|work=[[All Movie Guide]] |first=Andrea|last=LeVasseur|publisher=Starpulse|year=2003}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/64/Giancarlo-Esposito.html|title=Giancarlo Esposito Biography (1958\u2013)|accessdate=2009-04-10|website=Film Reference|publisher=NetIndustries, LLC|quote=Giancarlo Giuseppi Alessandro Esposito; born April 26, 1958, in Copenhagen, Denmark; raised in New York, N.Y., father, a stagehand and carpenter; mother, an opera and nightclub singer; married Joy McManigal (a producer), June 1995; children: Shayne Lyra, Kale Lyn}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-dotheright-giancarlo-esposito_kjp6tinc,0,5112312.photo|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Giancarlo Esposito and confrontation}}</ref>\n\nWhen Esposito was six, his family moved from [[Copenhagen]], Denmark to [[Manhattan]], New York. He attended [[Elizabeth Seton College]] in New York and earned a two-year degree in radio and television communications.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Giancarlo Esposito heads to Reggae Film Festival|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120326/ent/ent1.html|date=March 26, 2012|work=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=2016-01-23}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nEsposito made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut at age eight, playing a [[Slavery|slave child]] opposite [[Shirley Jones]] in the short-lived musical ''[[Maggie Flynn]]'' (1968), set during the [[New York Draft Riots of 1863]].<ref>[http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Esposito,_Giancarlo/Biography/ \"Bio: Giancarlo Esposito\"], Starpulse.com; accessed June 14, 2017.</ref> He was also a member of the youthful cast of the [[Stephen Sondheim]]-[[Harold Prince]] collaboration [[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|''Merrily We Roll Along'']], which closed with 16 performances and 56 previews in 1981.\n\nDuring the 1980s, Esposito appeared in films such as ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]'', ''[[Maximum Overdrive]],'' ''[[King of New York]],'' and ''[[Trading Places]].'' He also performed in TV shows such as ''[[Miami Vice]]'' and ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]''. He played J. C. Pierce, a cadet in the 1981 movie ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0002064/filmotype/actor?ref_=m_nmfm_2 | title=Giancarlo Esposito}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988 he landed his breakout role as the leader (\"Dean Big Brother Almighty\") of the black fraternity \"Gamma Phi Gamma\" in [[film director|director]] [[Spike Lee]]'s film ''[[School Daze]],'' exploring color relations at black colleges. Over the next four years, Esposito and Lee collaborated on three other movies: ''[[Do the Right Thing]],'' ''[[Mo' Better Blues]],'' and ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.\nDuring the 1990s Esposito appeared in the acclaimed indie films ''[[Night on Earth]]'', ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]]'' and ''[[Smoke (film)|Smoke]],'' as well as its sequel ''[[Blue in the Face]]''. He also appeared in the mainstream film ''[[Reckless (1995 film)|Reckless]]'' with [[Mia Farrow]], and ''[[Waiting to Exhale]]'' starring [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Angela Bassett]]. In 1995 Esposito was featured in a music video \"California\" by French superstar Mylene Farmer, directed by Abel Ferrara.\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Esposito 1998.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Esposito in 1998]]\n\nEsposito played FBI agent [[Mike Giardello]] on the TV crime drama ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''. That role drew from both his African American and [[Italian people|Italian]] ancestry. He played this character during the show's seventh and final season. Mike's estranged father, shift lieutenant [[Al Giardello]], is portrayed as subject to [[racism]], something Esposito's character practiced in ''[[School Daze]].'' Another multiracial role was as Sergeant Paul Gigante in the television comedy, ''[[Bakersfield P.D.]]''.\n\nIn 1997 Esposito played the film roles of Darryl in ''[[Trouble on the Corner]]'' and Charlie Dunt in ''[[Nothing to Lose (1997 film)|Nothing to Lose]]''. Other TV credits include ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[The Practice]]'', ''[[New York Undercover]]'', and ''[[List of Fallen Angels episodes|Fallen Angels: Fearless]]''.\n\nEsposito has portrayed drug dealers (''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]],'' ''[[Breaking Bad (TV series)|Breaking Bad]],'' ''[[King of New York]],'' ''Better Call Saul''), policemen (''[[The Usual Suspects]],'' ''[[Derailed (2005 film)|Derailed]]''), [[Extremism|political radicals]] (''[[Bob Roberts]], [[Do the Right Thing]]''), and a [[demon]]ic version of the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] God of Sleep [[Hypnos]] from another dimension (''[[Monkeybone]]''). In 2001, he played [[Cassius Marcellus Clay, Sr.]] in ''[[Ali (movie)|Ali]]'', and [[Miguel Algar\u00edn]], friend and collaborator of [[Nuyorican]] poet [[Miguel Pi\u00f1ero]], in ''[[Pi\u00f1ero (movie)|Pi\u00f1ero]]''.\n\nIn 2006 Esposito starred in ''[[Last Holiday (2006 film)|Last Holiday]]'' as Senator Dillings, alongside [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Timothy Hutton]]. Also in 2006, he played an unsympathetic detective named Esposito in the 2005 film ''[[Hate Crime (2005 film)|Hate Crime]].'' The film explores [[homophobia]].\n\nEsposito played Robert Fuentes, a [[Miami]] businessman with shady connections, on the [[UPN]] television series ''[[South Beach (2006 TV series)|South Beach]].'' He has appeared in ''[[New Amsterdam (2008 TV series)|New Amsterdam]]'' and ''[[CSI: Miami]]''. In ''[[Feel the Noise]]'' (2007), he played ex-musician Roberto, the Puerto Rican father of Omarion Grandberry's character, aspiring rap star \"Rob\".\n\nHe made his directorial debut with ''[[Gospel Hill]]'' (2008); he also produced the film and starred in it.\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Esposito by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Esposito at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n\n[[Broadway theatre|New York theater]] credits for Esposito include ''[[The Me Nobody Knows]],'' ''[[Lost in the Stars]],'' ''[[Seesaw (musical)|Seesaw]],'' and ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]].'' In 2008 he appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] as Gooper in an [[African American]] production of [[Tennessee Williams]]' [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning drama ''[[Cat on a Hot Tin Roof]]'', directed by [[Debbie Allen]] and starring [[James Earl Jones]], [[Phylicia Rashad]], [[Anika Noni Rose]], and [[Terrence Howard]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nFrom 2009 to 2011, Esposito appeared in seasons 2 through 4 of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] drama ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', as [[Gus Fring]], the head of a [[New Mexico]]-based [[methamphetamine]] drug ring. In the fourth season, he was the show's primary antagonist. He received critical acclaim for this role. He won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama]] award at the [[Critics' Choice Television Award|2012 Critics' Choice Television Awards]] and was nominated for an [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards#Supporting performances|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] award at the [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012 Primetime Emmy Awards]], but lost to co-star [[Aaron Paul]].\n\nHe appeared in the film ''[[Rabbit Hole (film)|Rabbit Hole]]'' (2010).\n\nEsposito appeared in the first season of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] program ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]],'' which debuted in October 2011. He portrayed the split role of Sidney, a reporter for ''The Daily Mirror'' in the town of Storybrooke, Maine, who is the Magic Mirror, possessed by The Evil Queen in a parallel fairy tale world.<ref name=MagicMirror>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=TV BITS: Giancarlo Esposito To Join ABC Series, Howie Mandel To Produce Reality Format, Ben Silveran To Publish Comic|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/07/tv-bits-giancarlo-esposito-to-join-abc-series-howie-mandel-to-produce-reality-format-ben-silveran-to-publish-comic/|work=Deadline|publisher=Mail.com Media Corp.|date=July 18, 2011|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEsposito appeared in ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'' as Major Tom Neville, a central character who kills Ben Matheson in the pilot. He escorts a captured Danny to the capital Philadelphia of the Monroe Republic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Tom Neville|url=https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0336367|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEsposito also appeared in ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' as a guest star for the episode entitled \"[[Digital Estate Planning]]\". He performed again in the fourth season, in the episode titled \"Paranormal Parentage\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Giancarlo-Esposito-Community-1043497.aspx|title=Exclusive: Giancarlo Esposito Talks About His ''Community'' Guest Shot|work=TV Guide|first=David|last=Kronke|date=February 17, 2012|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> Esposito has additionally appeared in a video of the action role-playing sci-fi first-person shooter game ''[[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]]'', as well as plays The Dentist, a non-playable story character, in the game ''[[Payday 2]].''\n\nHe has joined the ''[[DC Universe Animated Original Movies]]'' series. He played [[Ra's al Ghul]] in ''[[Son of Batman]]'' and [[Black Spider]] in ''[[Batman: Assault on Arkham]]''. He had a recurring role in the first season of ''[[The Get Down]]'' on [[Netflix]]. In 2017, Esposito reprised his role as [[Gus Fring]] in the ''Breaking Bad'' prequel series, ''[[Better Call Saul]]''. In the show's second season, an anagram of the first letters of every episode name spelled out \"FRING'S BACK\", which was revealed to be intentional by showrunners [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]. Esposito appeared in a teaser for the third season portraying Gus as the [[Los Pollos Hermanos]] owner, officially confirming Esposito's involvement in the third season.\n\nIn 2016, Esposito voiced [[Akela (The Jungle Book)|Akela]] in the film ''[[The Jungle Book (2016 film)|The Jungle Book]]'', which was directed by [[Jon Favreau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/07/jungle-book-movie-christopher-walken-giancarlo-esposito-811101/|title=Disney's 'Jungle Book' Adds Christopher Walken & Giancarlo Esposito|author=The Deadline Team|work=Deadline|date=July 28, 2014|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> Esposito and Favreau would work together once again in the [[web series]] ''[[The Mandalorian]]'' in which Esposito appears in a starring role, while Favreau acts as an executive producer for the series and as its writer.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |title='Star Wars: The Mandalorian' Casting: Giancarlo Esposito, Carl Weathers And Werner Herzog Join Disney+ Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=December 12, 2018 |date=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe plays the role of NY congressman [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.]] in the 2019 Epix series ''[[Godfather of Harlem]]''.\n\n== Personal life ==\nEsposito married Joy McManigal in 1995; they later divorced. He has four daughters.<ref name=\"Heisler\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/giancarlo-esposito,62959/|title=Giancarlo Esposito|last=Heisler|first=Steve|date=October 7, 2011|work=AV Club|accessdate=October 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Running (film)|Running]]''\n| Puerto Rican Teenager\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]''\n| Cadet Captain JC Pierce\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Trading Places]]''\n| Cellmate\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''Enormous Changes at the Last Minute''\n| Julio\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (film)|Go Tell It on the Mountain]]''\n| Elisha\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Cotton Club (film)|The Cotton Club]]''\n| Bumpy Hood\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Desperately Seeking Susan]]''\n| Street Vendor\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Maximum Overdrive]]''\n| Videoplayer\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Sweet Lorraine]]''\n| Howie\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[School Daze]]''\n| Julian\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Do the Right Thing]]''\n| Buggin' Out\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]''\n| Left Hand Lacey\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[King of New York]]''\n| Lance\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]''\n| Jimmy Jiles\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Night on Earth]]''\n| YoYo\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Bob Roberts]]''\n| John Alijah \"Bugs\" Raplin\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''\n| [[Thomas Hagan]]\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|