|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Feel the Noise]]''\n| Roberto\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Gospel Hill]]''\n| Dr. Palmer\n| Also director and producer\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Rabbit Hole (film)|Rabbit Hole]]''\n| Auggie\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[S.W.A.T.: Firefight]]''\n| Inspector Hollander\n| Direct-to-DVD\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Certainty (film)|Certainty]]''\n| Father Heery\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Alex Cross (film)|Alex Cross]]''\n| Daramus Holiday\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Dreaming American''\n| Daytona LeMans\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Requiem for the Big East''\n| Narrator\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=ICYMI: The week on Front Row PLUS Inside new #BigEast 30 for 30 film debuting Sunday|url=http://frontrow.espn.go.com/2014/03/icymi-week-front-row-plus-inside-new-big-east-30-30-film/|last=Spender|first=Sheldon|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Son of Batman]]''\n| [[Ra's al Ghul]] (voice)\n| Direct-to-DVD\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Batman: Assault on Arkham]]''\n| [[Black Spider]] (voice)\n| Direct-to-DVD\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Poker Night (film)|Poker Night]]''\n| Bernard\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Maze Runner: The Scorch Trials]]''\n| Jorge\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''The Pills \u2013 Sempre meglio che lavorare'' <small>([[:it:The Pills \u2013 Sempre meglio che lavorare|it]])</small>\n| Bangla Boss\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Jungle Book (2016 film)|The Jungle Book]]''\n| [[Akela (The Jungle Book)|Akela]] (voice)\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Disney's 'Jungle Book' Adds Christopher Walken & Giancarlo Esposito|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/07/jungle-book-movie-christopher-walken-giancarlo-esposito/|accessdate=July 28, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=July 28, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Money Monster]]''\n| Captain Marcus Powell\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Brother Nature (film)|Brother Nature]]''\n| Congressman Frank McClaren\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Show (2017 film)|The Show]]''\n| Mason Washington\n| Also director and producer\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Stuck (2017 film)|Stuck]]''\n| Lloyd\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Okja]]''\n| Frank Dawson\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Unacknowledged''\n| Narrator\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure]]''\n| Jorge\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mutafukaz|MFKZ]]''\n| Mr. K (voice)\n| English dub\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Coda (2020 film)|Coda]]''\n| Paul\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Stargirl (film)|Stargirl]]''\n| Archie\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[The Long Home]]''\n| William Tell Oliver\n| Post-production\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Da 5 Bloods]]''\n|\n| Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[The Gentleman Bandit]]''\n| Jamie\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Finnegan Begin Again]]''\n| Intruder\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Rockabye (1986 film)|Rockabye]]''\n| Marcus\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''Stardust''\n| Mr. Peavy\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Creature (TV film)|Creature]]''\n| Lt. Thomas Peniston\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Thirst (1998 film)|Thirst]]''\n| Dr. Lawrence Carver\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[Naked City: Justice with a Bullet]]''\n| Chaz Villanueva\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Xenophobia''\n| Young\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Over / Under''\n| Oliver Ohrt\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Television series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Sesame Street]]''\n| Mickey\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]''\n| Willie Armstrong\n| Episode: \"4498\"\n|-\n| 1982\u20131983\n| ''[[Guiding Light]]''\n| Clay Tynan\n| Unknown episodes\n|-\n| 1984\u20131985\n| ''[[Miami Vice]]''\n| Luther, Ricky, Adonis Jackson\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[CBS Schoolbreak Special]]''\n| Kyle\n| Episode: \"The Exchange Student\"\n|-\n| 1985\u20131986\n| ''[[American Playhouse]]''\n| Elisha, Simon Fernandes\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Equalizer]]''\n| Jumpin' Jack\n| Episode: \"The Line\"\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]''\n| Ramos\n| Episode: \"On the Night He Was Betrayed\"\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Leg Work]]''\n| Tyson\n| Episode: \"Blind Trust\"\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Lifestories]]''\n| Julio\n| Episode: \"Jerry Forchette\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[The American Experience]]''\n| Dr. Kenneth Clark\n| Episode: \"Simple Justice\"\n|-\n| 1993\u20131994\n| ''[[Bakersfield P.D.]]''\n| Detective Paul Gigante\n| 17 episodes\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[New York Undercover]]''\n| Adolfo Guzman\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Fallen Angels (American TV series)|Fallen Angels]]''\n| Paris Minton\n| Episode: \"Fearless\"\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Chicago Hope]]''\n| Cherchez LaFemme\n| Episode: \"Right to Life\"\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Swift Justice]]''\n| Andrew Coffin\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1996; <br /> 1998\n| ''[[NYPD Blue]]''\n| Ferdinand Hollie, Jamaal\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Living Single]]''\n| Jackson Turner\n| Episode: \"Kiss of the Spider Man\"\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''The Tomorrow Man''\n| Jonathan Driscoll\n| Unsold TV pilot\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Mr. Baylor\n| Episode: \"Good Girl\"\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[The Hunger (TV series)|The Hunger]]''\n| Vampire\n| Episode: \"Fly-By-Night\"\n|-\n| 1998\u20131999\n| ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''\n| Federal Agent Mike Giardello\n| 22 episodes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Touched by an Angel]]''\n| Antonio\n| Episode: \"Here I Am\"\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Homicide: The Movie]]''\n| Officer Mike Giardello\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2000\u20132001\n| ''[[The Street (2000 TV series)|The $treet]]''\n| Tom Divack\n| 12 episodes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Strong Medicine]]''\n| James Bell\n| Episode: \"Mortality\"\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[100 Centre Street]]''\n| Jacob Lenz\n| Episode: \"Andromeda and the Monster\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[A Nero Wolfe Mystery]]''\n| Ambassador Theodore Kelefy\n| Episode: \"Immune to Murder\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Practice]]''\n| Ray McMurphy\n| Episode: \"Pro Se\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Third Watch]]''\n| Father Romero\n| Episode: \"The Unforgiven\"\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Girls Club (TV series)|Girls Club]]''\n| Nicholas Hahn\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2004\u20132005\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Rodney Fallon\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[5ive Days to Midnight]]''\n| Tim Sanders\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''NYPD 2069''\n| Lt. Garner\n| Unsold TV pilot\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Soul Food (TV series)|Soul Food]]''\n| Jules\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Law & Order: Trial by Jury]]''\n| Orlando Ramirez\n| Episode: \"Boys Will Be Boys\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[South Beach (2006 TV series)|South Beach]]''\n| Robert Fuentes\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''\n| Ely Fisher\n| Episode: \"Fury\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n| Richard Benoit\n| Episode: \"[[The Man in the Morgue]]\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]''\n| Reggie Archibald\n| Episode: \"White Christmas\"\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008\n| ''[[CSI: Miami]]''\n| Chief Braga\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Kidnapped (TV series)|Kidnapped]]''\n| Vance\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[New Amsterdam (2008 TV series)|New Amsterdam]]''\n| Special Agent James Lawson\n| Episode: \"Legacy\"\n|-\n| 2009\u20132011\n| ''[[Breaking Bad]]''\n| [[Gus Fring]]\n| Recurring (season 2); 2 episodes <br /> Main role (seasons 3-4); 22 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Leverage (TV series)|Leverage]]''\n| Alexander Moto\n| Episode: \"The Scheherazade Job\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Lie to Me]]''\n| Beau Hackman\n| Episode: \"Black and White\"\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Detroit 1-8-7]]''\n| Eddie Henderson\n| Episode: \"Shelter\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Criminal Minds: Suspect Behavior]]''\n| Gordon Ramirez\n| Episode: \"The Time is Now\"\n|-\n| 2011\u20132017\n| ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''\n| Sidney Glass / [[Magic Mirror (Snow White)|Magic Mirror]]\n| 14 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''\n| Gilbert Lawson\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[NYC 22]]''\n| Harvey Williams\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]''\n| Tom Neville\n| 41 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Timms Valley''\n| Pruit Normings (voice)\n| Unsold TV pilot\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Axe Cop (TV series)|Axe Cop]]''\n| Army Chihuahua (voice)\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Allegiance (TV series)|Allegiance]]''\n| Oscar Christoph\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Drunk History]]''\n| [[Andr\u00e9s Pico]]\n| Episode: \"Los Angeles\"\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[The Get Down]]''\n| Pastor Ramon Cruz\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Rebel (TV series)|Rebel]]''\n| Charles Gold\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u2013present\n| ''[[Better Call Saul]]''\n| Gus Fring\n| 17 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u2013present\n| ''[[Dear White People (TV series)|Dear White People]]''\n| Narrator (voice)\n| 23 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Westworld (TV series)|Westworld]]''\n| El Lazo / Robert Ford\n| Episode: \"[[Reunion (Westworld)|Reunion]]\"\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Dallas & Robo]]''\n| Victor Goldsmith (voice)\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Jett (TV series)|Jett]]''\n| Charlie Baudelaire\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Boys (2019 TV series)|The Boys]]''\n| Stan Edgar\n| Episode: \"You Found Me\"\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Godfather of Harlem]]''\n| [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.]]\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[Harley Quinn (TV series)|Harley Quinn]]''\n| [[Lex Luthor]] (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[The Mandalorian]]''\n| [[Moff Gideon]]\n| Recurring; 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[DuckTales (2017 TV series)|DuckTales]]''\n| TBA\n|\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Payday 2]]''\n| The Dentist\n| Also likeness\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]]''\n| Father\n| Trailer\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[Independent Spirit Awards]]\n| [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Male|Best Supporting Male]]\n| ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[National Board of Review]]\n| [[National Board of Review Award for Best Cast|Best Cast]]\n| ''[[The Usual Suspects]]''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1999\n| rowspan=2| [[NAACP Image Awards]]\n| rowspan=2| [[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| rowspan=7| ''[[Breaking Bad]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Saturn Award]]s\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Guest Starring Role on Television|Best Guest Starring Role on Television]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]s\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| Saturn Awards\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor on Television|Best Supporting Actor on Television]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2012\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2013\n| Saturn Awards\n| Best Supporting Actor on Television\n| ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2019\n| Screen Actors Guild Awards\n| Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n| rowspan=2| ''[[Better Call Saul]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2019\n| Primetime Emmy Awards\n| Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0002064|Giancarlo Esposito}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{AllMovie name|22133|Giancarlo Esposito}}\n\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Esposito, Giancarlo}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Male actors of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:American people of Campanian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actor and director}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| image              = Giancarlo Esposito SXSW 2017 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Esposito at the 2017 [[South by Southwest]] Festival\n| birth_name         = Giancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1958|4|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| nationality        = American, Italian\n| occupation         = Actor and director\n| yearsactive        = 1966\u2013present\n| spouse             = Joy McManigal<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 1995; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 2015)\n| children           = 4\n}}\n\n'''Giancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito''' ({{IPA-it|d\u0292a\u014b\u02c8karlo d\u0292u\u02c8z\u025bppe ales\u02c8sandro e\u02c8sp\u0254\u02d0zito}}; born 26 April 1958) is an Italian-American actor and director. He has played [[Gus Fring|Gustavo \"Gus\" Fring]] on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] shows ''[[Breaking Bad]]'' and also plays the character on ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', a role for which he won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama Series Award]] at the [[Critics' Choice Television Award|2012 Critics' Choice Television Awards]] and was nominated for an [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards#Supporting performances|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] at the [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012 Primetime Emmy Awards]] and again at the [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019 Primetime Emmy Awards]]. He appeared as [[Moff Gideon]] in the live-action ''[[Star Wars]]'' series ''[[The Mandalorian]]'' on [[Disney+]] which premiered in 2019.\n\nHe has appeared in [[Spike Lee]] films such as ''[[Do the Right Thing]]'', ''[[School Daze]]'', and ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]''. His feature film appearances include ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]]'', ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]'', ''[[The Usual Suspects]]'', and ''[[King of New York]]''. He has played Tom Neville in the [[NBC]] series ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'' and Sidney Glass / [[Magic Mirror (Snow White)|Magic Mirror]] on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]''. He has had roles in two [[Netflix]] original series: ''[[The Get Down]]'', wherein he portrays Pastor Ramon Cruz, and ''[[Dear White People (TV series)|Dear White People]]'', which he narrates. He also voiced and portrayed \"The Dentist\" in the video game ''[[Payday 2]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGiancarlo Giuseppe Alessandro Esposito was born in [[Copenhagen]], the son of Giovanni Esposito aka John C. Esposito (1931-2002), an [[Italians|Italian]] stagehand and carpenter from [[Naples]], and Elizabeth Foster aka Leesa Foster (1926-2017), an [[African-American]] opera and nightclub singer from [[Alabama]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te8TCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Giovanni+Esposito+elizabeth+foster|title=Feeling Italian: The Art of Ethnicity in America|last=Ferraro|first=Thomas J.|date=2005|isbn=9780814727300}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Esposito,_Giancarlo/Biography/|title=Giancarlo Esposito Pictures, Biography, Filmography, News, Videos|accessdate=2009-04-10|work=[[All Movie Guide]] |first=Andrea|last=LeVasseur|publisher=Starpulse|year=2003}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/64/Giancarlo-Esposito.html|title=Giancarlo Esposito Biography (1958\u2013)|accessdate=2009-04-10|website=Film Reference|publisher=NetIndustries, LLC|quote=Giancarlo Giuseppi Alessandro Esposito; born April 26, 1958, in Copenhagen, Denmark; raised in New York, N.Y., father, a stagehand and carpenter; mother, an opera and nightclub singer; married Joy McManigal (a producer), June 1995; children: Shayne Lyra, Kale Lyn}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/la-dotheright-giancarlo-esposito_kjp6tinc,0,5112312.photo|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Giancarlo Esposito and confrontation}}</ref>\n\nWhen Esposito was six, his family moved from [[Copenhagen|Copenhagen, Denmark]] to [[Manhattan|Manhattan, New York]]. He attended [[Elizabeth Seton College]] in New York and earned a two-year degree in radio and television communications.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Giancarlo Esposito heads to Reggae Film Festival|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120326/ent/ent1.html|date=March 26, 2012|work=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=2016-01-23}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nEsposito made his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut at age eight, playing a [[Slavery|slave child]] opposite [[Shirley Jones]] in the short-lived musical ''[[Maggie Flynn]]'' (1968), set during the [[New York Draft Riots of 1863]].<ref>[http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Esposito,_Giancarlo/Biography/ \"Bio: Giancarlo Esposito\"], Starpulse.com; accessed June 14, 2017.</ref> He was also a member of the youthful cast of the [[Stephen Sondheim]]-[[Harold Prince]] collaboration [[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|''Merrily We Roll Along'']], which closed with 16 performances and 56 previews in 1981.\n\nDuring the 1980s, Esposito appeared in films such as ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]'', ''[[Maximum Overdrive]],'' ''[[King of New York]],'' and ''[[Trading Places]].'' He also performed in TV shows such as ''[[Miami Vice]]'' and ''[[Spenser: For Hire]]''. He played J. C. Pierce, a cadet in the 1981 movie ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]''.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0002064/filmotype/actor?ref_=m_nmfm_2 | title=Giancarlo Esposito}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988 he landed his breakout role as the leader (\"Dean Big Brother Almighty\") of the black fraternity \"Gamma Phi Gamma\" in [[film director|director]] [[Spike Lee]]'s film ''[[School Daze]],'' exploring color relations at black colleges. Over the next four years, Esposito and Lee collaborated on three other movies: ''[[Do the Right Thing]],'' ''[[Mo' Better Blues]],'' and ''[[Malcolm X (1992 film)|Malcolm X]]''.\nDuring the 1990s Esposito appeared in the acclaimed indie films ''[[Night on Earth]]'', ''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]]'' and ''[[Smoke (film)|Smoke]],'' as well as its sequel ''[[Blue in the Face]]''. He also appeared in the mainstream film ''[[Reckless (1995 film)|Reckless]]'' with [[Mia Farrow]], and ''[[Waiting to Exhale]]'' starring [[Whitney Houston]] and [[Angela Bassett]]. In 1995 Esposito was featured in a music video \"California\" by French superstar Mylene Farmer, directed by Abel Ferrara.\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Esposito 1998.jpg|left|upright|thumb|Esposito in 1998]]\n\nEsposito played FBI agent [[Mike Giardello]] on the TV crime drama ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]''. That role drew from both his African American and [[Italian people|Italian]] ancestry. He played this character during the show's seventh and final season. Mike's estranged father, shift lieutenant [[Al Giardello]], is portrayed as subject to [[racism]], something Esposito's character practiced in ''[[School Daze]].'' Another multiracial role was as Sergeant Paul Gigante in the television comedy, ''[[Bakersfield P.D.]]''.\n\nIn 1997 Esposito played the film roles of Darryl in ''[[Trouble on the Corner]]'' and Charlie Dunt in ''[[Nothing to Lose (1997 film)|Nothing to Lose]]''. Other TV credits include ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[The Practice]]'', ''[[New York Undercover]]'', and ''[[List of Fallen Angels episodes|Fallen Angels: Fearless]]''.\n\nEsposito has portrayed drug dealers (''[[Fresh (1994 film)|Fresh]],'' ''[[Breaking Bad (TV series)|Breaking Bad]],'' ''[[King of New York]],'' ''Better Call Saul''), policemen (''[[The Usual Suspects]],'' ''[[Derailed (2005 film)|Derailed]]''), [[Extremism|political radicals]] (''[[Bob Roberts]], [[Do the Right Thing]]''), and a [[demon]]ic version of the [[Greek mythology|Greek]] God of Sleep [[Hypnos]] from another dimension (''[[Monkeybone]]''). In 2001, he played [[Cassius Marcellus Clay, Sr.]] in ''[[Ali (movie)|Ali]]'', and [[Miguel Algar\u00edn]], friend and collaborator of [[Nuyorican]] poet [[Miguel Pi\u00f1ero]], in ''[[Pi\u00f1ero (movie)|Pi\u00f1ero]]''.\n\nIn 2006 Esposito starred in ''[[Last Holiday (2006 film)|Last Holiday]]'' as Senator Dillings, alongside [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Timothy Hutton]]. Also in 2006, he played an unsympathetic detective named Esposito in the 2005 film ''[[Hate Crime (2005 film)|Hate Crime]].'' The film explores [[homophobia]].\n\nEsposito played Robert Fuentes, a [[Miami]] businessman with shady connections, on the [[UPN]] television series ''[[South Beach (2006 TV series)|South Beach]].'' He has appeared in ''[[New Amsterdam (2008 TV series)|New Amsterdam]]'' and ''[[CSI: Miami]]''. In ''[[Feel the Noise]]'' (2007), he played ex-musician Roberto, the Puerto Rican father of Omarion Grandberry's character, aspiring rap star \"Rob\".\n\nHe made his directorial debut with ''[[Gospel Hill]]'' (2008); he also produced the film and starred in it.\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Esposito by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Esposito at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]]]\n\n[[Broadway theatre|New York theater]] credits for Esposito include ''[[The Me Nobody Knows]],'' ''[[Lost in the Stars]],'' ''[[Seesaw (musical)|Seesaw]],'' and ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]].'' In 2008 he appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] as Gooper in an [[African American]] production of [[Tennessee Williams]]' [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning drama ''[[Cat on a Hot Tin Roof]]'', directed by [[Debbie Allen]] and starring [[James Earl Jones]], [[Phylicia Rashad]], [[Anika Noni Rose]], and [[Terrence Howard]].{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nFrom 2009 to 2011, Esposito appeared in seasons 2 through 4 of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] drama ''[[Breaking Bad]]'', as [[Gus Fring]], the head of a [[New Mexico]]-based [[methamphetamine]] drug ring. In the fourth season, he was the show's primary antagonist. He received critical acclaim for this role. He won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Drama Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor in a Drama]] award at the [[Critics' Choice Television Award|2012 Critics' Choice Television Awards]] and was nominated for an [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards#Supporting performances|Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Drama Series]] award at the [[64th Primetime Emmy Awards|2012 Primetime Emmy Awards]], but lost to co-star [[Aaron Paul]]. \n\nHe appeared in the film ''[[Rabbit Hole (film)|Rabbit Hole]]'' (2010).\n\nEsposito appeared in the first season of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] program ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]],'' which debuted in October 2011. He portrayed the split role of Sidney, a reporter for ''The Daily Mirror'' in the town of Storybrooke, Maine, who is the Magic Mirror, possessed by The Evil Queen in a parallel fairy tale world.<ref name=MagicMirror>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=TV BITS: Giancarlo Esposito To Join ABC Series, Howie Mandel To Produce Reality Format, Ben Silveran To Publish Comic|url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/07/tv-bits-giancarlo-esposito-to-join-abc-series-howie-mandel-to-produce-reality-format-ben-silveran-to-publish-comic/|work=Deadline|publisher=Mail.com Media Corp.|date=July 18, 2011|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nEsposito appeared in ''[[Revolution (TV series)|Revolution]]'' as Major Tom Neville, a central character who kills Ben Matheson in the pilot. He escorts a captured Danny to the capital Philadelphia of the Monroe Republic.<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Tom Neville|url=https://www.imdb.com/character/ch0336367|publisher=IMDB|accessdate=April 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEsposito also appeared in ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' as a guest star for the episode entitled \"[[Digital Estate Planning]]\". He performed again in the fourth season, in the episode titled \"Paranormal Parentage\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Giancarlo-Esposito-Community-1043497.aspx|title=Exclusive: Giancarlo Esposito Talks About His ''Community'' Guest Shot|work=TV Guide|first=David|last=Kronke|date=February 17, 2012|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref> Esposito has additionally appeared in a video of the action role-playing sci-fi first-person shooter game ''[[Destiny (video game)|Destiny]]'', as well as plays The Dentist, a non-playable story character, in the game ''[[Payday 2]].''\n\nHe has joined the ''[[DC Universe Animated Original Movies]]'' series. He played [[Ra's al Ghul]] in ''[[Son of Batman]]'' and [[Black Spider]] in ''[[Batman: Assault on Arkham]]''. He had a recurring role in the first season of ''[[The Get Down]]'' on [[Netflix]]. In 2017, Esposito reprised his role as [[Gus Fring]] in the ''Breaking Bad'' prequel series, ''[[Better Call Saul]]''. In the show's second season, an anagram of the first letters of every episode name spelled out \"FRING'S BACK\", which was revealed to be intentional by showrunners [[Vince Gilligan]] and [[Peter Gould (writer)|Peter Gould]]. Esposito appeared in a teaser for the third season portraying Gus as the Los Pollos Hermanos owner, officially confirming Esposito's involvement in the third season.\n\nIn 2016, Esposito voiced [[Akela (The Jungle Book)|Akela]] in the film ''[[The Jungle Book (2016 film)|The Jungle Book]]'', which was directed by [[Jon Favreau]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/07/jungle-book-movie-christopher-walken-giancarlo-esposito-811101/|title=Disney's 'Jungle Book' Adds Christopher Walken & Giancarlo Esposito|author=The Deadline Team|work=Deadline|date=July 28, 2014|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> Esposito and Favreau would work together once again in the [[web series]] ''[[The Mandalorian]]'' in which Esposito appears in a starring role, while Favreau acts as an executive producer for the series and as its writer.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |title='Star Wars: The Mandalorian' Casting: Giancarlo Esposito, Carl Weathers And Werner Herzog Join Disney+ Series |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/star-wars-the-mandaloriancast-disney-favreau-jedi-pascal-pedro-1202518897/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=December 12, 2018 |date=December 12, 2018}}</ref>\nHe plays the role of NY congressman [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.]] in the 2019 Epix series ''[[Godfather of Harlem]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nEsposito married Joy McManigal in 1995; they later divorced. He has four daughters.<ref name=\"Heisler\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/giancarlo-esposito,62959/|title=Giancarlo Esposito|last=Heisler|first=Steve|date=October 7, 2011|work=AV Club|accessdate=October 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Running (film)|Running]]''\n| Puerto Rican Teenager\n| \n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Taps (film)|Taps]]''\n| Cadet Captain JC Pierce\n| \n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Trading Places]]''\n| Cellmate\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''Enormous Changes at the Last Minute''\n| Julio\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (film)|Go Tell It on the Mountain]]''\n| Elisha\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[The Cotton Club (film)|The Cotton Club]]'